In a GLSL shader by specifications "The #version directive must occur in a shader before anything else, except for comments and white space.".
This can be a problem because we add "#define COMPILEVS/PS" first.
nVidia never bothers with spec too much and infact it works, but AMD could have done it right. I don't have an ATI hardware but their shader analyzer throws an error, also I think the MESA compiler complains (I see the error in the GLSL-Debugger).
If you think this is an issue we can use this to find the version directive:

```
    const char VER_DRC[] = "#version ";
    bool findEndLine = false;
    bool foundVersion = false;
    unsigned pos;
    for (pos = 0; pos < originalShaderCode.Length(); ++pos)
    {
        char c = originalShaderCode[pos];
        if (findEndLine)
        {
            if (c == '\n')
                findEndLine = false;
            continue;
        }
        if (foundVersion)
            break;
        if (c == ' ')
            continue;
        if (c == '#' && memcmp(VER_DRC, originalShaderCode.CString()+pos, sizeof(VER_DRC)-1) == 0)
        {
            findEndLine = true;
            foundVersion = true;
        }
        else if (c == '/')
            findEndLine = true;
        else
            break;
    }
```

